objects.name: jolly jellyfish
objects.description: Jolly Jellyfish is a non-persistent Windows downloader that retrieves and executes shellcode hidden within BMP image files using steganography. It downloads the BMP over HTTP, extracts the shellcode by reading every fourth byte from the pixel array (max ~1900 bytes, null-terminated), and executes it; the shellcode is a Cobalt Strike stager configured with a C2 at download.google-images[.]ml and GET URI /kXe5. Some variants XOR-obfuscate the shellcode (e.g., using keys misgat_mg and mait_mg), display a Chinese-language message box to support social engineering (e.g., masquerading as a browser plugin update), and/or download and execute apparently legitimate files (e.g., a MonPass client). The malware employs anti-sandbox checks (memory >1GB, disk >1GB, logical processors >0) and short sleep delays for evasion. Samples include the string "BidenHappyHappyHappy" and a PDB path referencing "fishmaster", which appears to be the author’s internal name for the malware. No persistence is implemented.

objects.name: Virtualization/Sandbox Evasion: System Checks
objects.description: Jolly Jellyfish checks the available memory is greater than 1GB, the size of the disk is greater than 1GB, and the number of logical processors is greater than 0. These checks are designed to avoid running on a machine with low resources, as virtual machines and sandboxes are more likely to have low resources. If these checks fail the process will exit before any malicious behaviour occurs, avoiding detection.

objects.name: Virtualization/Sandbox Evasion: Time Based Evasion
objects.description: Jolly Jellyfish adds short sleep commands throughout execution, which could be an attempt to slow down execution enough to evade detection by automated analysis platforms.

objects.name: Application Layer Protocol: Web Protocols
objects.description: Jolly Jellyfish downloads shellcode over HTTP.

objects.name: Data obfuscation
objects.description: Some variants of Jolly Jellyfish download XOR-encoded shellcode.

objects.name: Data obfuscation: Steganography
objects.description: Jolly Jellyfish downloads shellcode contained within bitmap image (BMP) files.

objects.name: JollyJellyfish_unique_string_Bidenhappyhappyhappy
objects.description: YARA rule to detect related activity.
objects.pattern:
rule JollyJellyfish_unique_string_Bidenhappyhappyhappy
{
    meta:
        author = "NCSC"
        description = "Detects the “Bidenhappyhappyhappy” string used by
the Jolly Jellyfish malware"
        date = "2021-12-15"
        hash1 = "e99d5a620a488133f4da24e1f8d2d5e68542b6f3"
        hash2 = "834e80f6fa9935fd3184c25e4e37b0a068a773ee"
        hash3 = "d28eacb1b4d2e9ef54f7dff09ca03a6866fc9184"
        hash4 = "ba5558d79dadc12bbbe07e3444441d51d5e5931e"

    strings:
        $1 = "Bidenhappyhappyhappy"

    condition:
        uint16(0) == 0x5A4D and
        uint32(uint32(0x3c)) == 0x00004550 and
        all of them
}

greater than 1GB"
        date = "2021-12-15"
        hash1 = "e99d5a620a488133f4da24e1f8d2d5e68542b6f3"

        hash4 = "ba5558d79dadc12bbbe07e3444441d51d5e5931e"

        $1 = {33 D2 48 8B 44 ?? 38 B9 00 04 00 00 48 F7 F1 33 D2 B9 00 04

        $2 = {48 8B 44 ?? 38 48 C1 E8 14 ?? 00 04 00 00}
    condition:
        uint16(0) == 0x5A4D and
        uint32(uint32(0x3c)) == 0x00004550 and

        hash2 = "d28eacb1b4d2e9ef54f7dff09ca03a6866fc9184"

        hash4 = "ba5558d79dadc12bbbe07e3444441d51d5e5931e"

    strings:
        $1 = {48 89 84 24 ?? 00 00 00 48 8B 84 24 ?? 00 00 00 8B 40 0A 48
8B 4C 24 ?? 48 8D 44 01 03}
        $2 = {8B 43 0A 48 83 C0 03 48 03 D8}
    condition:
        uint16(0) == 0x5A4D and
        uint32(uint32(0x3c)) == 0x00004550 and
        any of them
